Q.1. Who is the author of this title “Allergy”?
(A) Premchand
(B) Puran Singh
(C) Dr. Rana S. P. Singh
(D) None of these
Answer: (C) Dr. Rana S. P. SinghExplanation: The lesson “Allergy” is written by Dr. Rana S. P. Singh.

Q.2. What is allergy?
(A) A malfunction of human immune system
(B) A Genetic disease
(C) A disease caused by Pollution
(D) None of these
Answer: (A) A malfunction of human immune systemExplanation: Allergy happens when the immune system reacts abnormally to harmless substances.

Q.3. Which of the following is caused by Allergy?
(A) Fever
(B) Eczema
(C) Asthma
(D) All of the above
Answer: (D) All of the aboveExplanation: Allergy can cause eczema, asthma, fever, and other problems.

Q.4. How can Allergic diseases be treated?
(A) By avoidance of the allergen
(B) By taking anti-allergic medicine
(C) By taking anti-allergic doses
(D) (A) & (B)
Answer: (D) (A) & (B)Explanation: Allergy can be treated by avoiding allergens and taking medicines.

Q.5. What is suggested to avoid allergy?
(A) Wear a pollen mask when mowing the grass
(B) Stay indoors in the morning and on windy days
(C) Read and understand food labels
(D) All of the above
Answer: (D) All of the aboveExplanation: All these steps help in preventing allergy.

Q.6. In this lesson, the author talks about different types of:
(A) Allergies
(B) Medicine
(C) Doctors
(D) Hospitals
Answer: (A) AllergiesExplanation: The lesson explains different types of allergies.

Q.7. A person has to be exposed to the particular………………..for some time to become allergic to it.
(A) Symptom
(B) Antigen
(C) Allergen
(D) Protein
Answer: (C) AllergenExplanation: Allergy develops when a person is exposed to an allergen.

Q.8. The path of allergy development is widely referred to as “the allergy march.”
(A) Side
(B) Twisted
(C) Direct
(D) Indirect
Answer: (C) DirectExplanation: The allergy march refers to the direct path of allergy development.

Q.9. The clinical use of inhaled ………………….. is currently gaining ground due to their anti-inflammatory effects.
(A) Steroids
(B) Proteins
(C) Allergens
(D) Antibodies
Answer: (A) SteroidsExplanation: Inhaled steroids are used to reduce inflammation in allergy and asthma.

Q.10. Sheets, mattress pads and blankets should be washed……………..in hot water.
(A) Monthly
(B) Daily
(C) Weekly
(D) Yearly
Answer: (C) WeeklyExplanation: Washing weekly helps remove allergens like dust mites.

Q.11. How many general approaches are there to the treatment of allergic diseases?
(A) 2
(B) 3
(C) 4
(D) 5
Answer: (B) 3Explanation: There are three approaches to treat allergy: avoidance, medicine, and immunotherapy.

Q.12. Which one of the following is a suggestion to avoid allergen?
(A) Allow dander-producing animals in the house
(B) Read and understand food labels
(C) Don’t enclose mattress, box springs and pillows in plastic barrier cloth
(D) none of these
Answer: (B) Read and understand food labelsExplanation: Reading food labels helps avoid allergy-causing foods.

Q.13. For effective asthma treatment, it is important for a person to consider some other things too besides the obvious signs of the disease.
(A) True
(B) False
(C) Both
(D) None
Answer: (A) TrueExplanation: Asthma treatment includes avoiding triggers and proper medication.

Q.14. Often at first, allergy appears in a…………….form.
(A) Allergen
(B) Dew
(C) Mild
(D) None of these
Answer: (C) MildExplanation: Allergy often begins in a mild form.

Q.15. Genetic and environment risk factors can cause:
(A) Immune
(B) Mild
(C) Allergies
(D) Antibody
Answer: (C) allergiesExplanation: Both genetic and environmental factors can cause allergies.

Q.16. What is the full form of ECP?
(A) Economic Cationic Protein
(B) Elementary Cationic Protein
(C) Effective Current Phosphate
(D) Eosinophilic Cationic Protein
Answer: (D) Eosinophilic Cationic ProteinExplanation: ECP is a protein related to allergic reactions.

Q.17. Our basic understanding of allergy has evolved from the discovery in ………………
(A) 1960
(B) 1965
(C) 1966
(D) 1967
Answer: (D) 1967Explanation: Important allergy research discoveries were made in 1967.

Q.18. The two scientists-Uppsala and Baltimore discovered immunoglobulin E or IgE antibodies in:
(A) 1866
(B) 1867
(C) 1986
(D) 1967
Answer: (D) 1967Explanation: IgE antibodies were discovered in 1967.

Q.19. The most troublesome allergen in North America is:
(A) Allergies
(B) Ragweed
(C) Ragweed pollen
(D) Itching and paining
Answer: (C) Ragweed pollenExplanation: Ragweed pollen is a common allergen in North America.

Q.20. What is IgE?
(A) Allergy
(B) Antibody
(C) Allergen
(D) None of these
Answer: (B) antibodyExplanation: IgE is an antibody related to allergic reactions.

Q.21. IgE antibodies is that they can be specific for hundreds of different:
(A) Allergy
(B) Allergens
(C) Antibodies
(D) Diseased
Answer: (B) allergensExplanation: IgE antibodies react with different allergens.

Q.22. Allergens are of……………..
(A) Two types
(B) Three types
(C) Four types
(D) Many types
Answer: (A) two typesExplanation: Allergens are mainly of two types: indoor and outdoor.

Q.23. What are allergens?
(A) Allergic remedy
(B) Harmful
(C) Substances producing allergic reaction
(D) Harmless substances
Answer: (C) substances producing allergic reactionExplanation: Allergens are substances that cause allergic reactions.

Q.24. Dr. Rana S. P. Singh was born on:
(A) 23 January 1976
(B) 28 January 1976
(C) 23 March 1879
(D) 18 January 1896
Answer: (A) 23 January 1976Explanation: Dr. Rana S. P. Singh was born on 23 January 1976.

Q.25. A powder produced by the male part of a flower:
(A) Allergy
(B) Poll
(C) Pollen
(D) Allergen
Answer: (C) PollenExplanation: Pollen is a powder produced by the male part of a flower and can cause allergy.

Q.26. IgE was discovered in:
(A) 1837
(B) 1867
(C) 1967
(D) 1957
Answer: (C) 1967Explanation: IgE antibody was discovered in 1967.

Q.27. ECP is a:
(A) Allergy
(B) Milk
(C) Protein
(D) Allergen
Answer: (C) ProteinExplanation: ECP is a protein related to allergic reactions.
